<div id="review_2994028471" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2994028471" />
    <a title="Norma Jean" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2776941-norma-jean"><img alt="Norma Jean" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560107112p2/2776941.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2994028471?book_show_action=true">Sep 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Norma Jean" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Norma Jean" href="/user/show/2776941-norma-jean">Norma Jean</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2776941-norma-jean?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2994028471" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14152618550385011473">After reading Elizabeth Alder&apos;s &quot;The Last Time I Saw Paris&quot; and &quot;Summer in Tuscany,&quot; both mostly travelogues with romance thrown in, this was a welcomed change. Down on her luck Daisy Keane has been jilted by her husband for the proverbial younger woman. She is rescued by incredibly wealthy Sir Robert Waldo Hardwick (think unattractive male and a &quot;My Fair Lady&quot; theme here). He feels she has enough grit and gumption to be trained as his Executive Assistant. She proves him right and then he is kil</span>
  <span id="freeText14152618550385011473" style="display:none">After reading Elizabeth Alder's "The Last Time I Saw Paris" and "Summer in Tuscany," both mostly travelogues with romance thrown in, this was a welcomed change. Down on her luck Daisy Keane has been jilted by her husband for the proverbial younger woman. She is rescued by incredibly wealthy Sir Robert Waldo Hardwick (think unattractive male and a "My Fair Lady" theme here). He feels she has enough grit and gumption to be trained as his Executive Assistant. She proves him right and then he is killed in a car accident--or is it? He had had a permonition that someone might be trying to kill him. After that, the book becomes more of the game of Clue by putting all of his potential suspects on a yacht to Capri for Daisy and his private investigator friend and employee, Harry Montana, to figure out who dun it. <br /><br />A light but fun read with Adler's ever present travelogue comments of the areas she mentions. I gave it 5 stars because I felt it had more substance than the two aforementioned books of hers.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14152618550385011473" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


